
**file types in linux**
1. regular files (-)
--these files save commanly used data such as text,script,images etc

2. directory files (d)
--these files are also called folder/directory. and are used to organize files and other subfolder/dir

3. Special files :
i] block file (b)
ii]char file (c)
iii] link file (l)<------
iv] socket file (s)
v] pipe file (p)

--> normal users mostly work with normal files, directories and link files.
-->you do not manually work with other files linux itself uses them internally.
-->the terminal(bash/zsh) uses a clor scheme called LS_COLORS to help you
visually identify file types easily.
white = normal file
blue = directory
green = executable file
cyan = link file
yellow background = block/char file
red = archive/ compressed
pink/purple = image

file <file_name>
--> to identify file type
